The MSS. of Juvenal may be divided into two classes, the one very numerously represented (Ruperti gives a list of 46) but comparatively worthless for critical purposes, the other represented now by only one com- plete codex but this of the greatest value in determining the text.

The fonner class may be dismissed in a few words They are usually called the interpolated MSS. and are scattered about in all the principal librarios throughout Europe. Though of course differing from one another in various details, seme being more, some less, carefully copied by the scribes, they seem all of them to follow not the original text of Juvenal, buta revised and corrected version of it, which was probably the work of some grammarian in the fifth or sixth century.
